.TH HSH 1 "APRIL 2026" "Project Simple Shell" "User Manual"
.SH NAME
hsh \- Simple shell command language interpreter
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B ./hsh
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B hsh
is a simplified command-line interpreter that replicates the basic functionality of \fB/bin/sh\fR. It reads commands from standard input, parses them, and executes the corresponding binaries.
.PP
The shell supports both \fBinteractive\fR and \fBnon-interactive\fR modes:
.IP "\(bu"
In \fBinteractive mode\fR, a prompt \fB($)\fR is displayed if the input is a terminal (checked via \fBisatty(3)\fR).
.IP "\(bu"
In \fBnon-interactive mode\fR, the shell reads commands directly from a pipe or redirected file without displaying a prompt.

.SH EXECUTION LOGIC
The shell execution flow is based on the following architecture:
.TP
.B 1. Input Processing (main.c)
The shell uses \fBgetline(3)\fR to read a full line from \fBstdin\fR. Memory is dynamically allocated and managed to prevent leaks.
.TP
.B 2. Tokenization (shell.c)
The \fBsplit_string\fR function breaks the input line into an array of strings (\fBargs\fR) using \fBstrtok(3)\fR with space as the delimiter.
.TP
.B 3. Path Resolution (find_path.c)
If the command does not contain a slash (\fB/\fR), the shell searches through the directories listed in the \fBPATH\fR environment variable. It uses \fBstat(2)\fR to check existence and \fBaccess(2)\fR with \fBX_OK\fR to verify execution permissions.
.TP
.B 4. Process Execution (shell.c)
A child process is created via \fBfork(2)\fR.
.RS
.IP "\(bu"
The child process uses \fBexecve(2)\fR to execute the binary with the provided arguments and environment.
.IP "\(bu"
The parent process uses \fBwait(2)\fR to wait for the child to complete and retrieves the exit status.
.TP
.B resolve_command
Resolve a command to it's full path
.TP
.B process_command
Parses and executes a command with its arguments
.RE

.SH BUILT-IN COMMANDS
The following commands are handled internally by \fBbuiltins.c\fR and do not trigger a fork:
.TP
.B exit
Terminates the shell process with exit status 0.

.SH EXIT STATUS
.IP "\(bu"
Returns the exit status of the last command executed.
.IP "\(bu"
Returns \fB127\fR if a command is not found.
.IP "\(bu"
Returns \fB0\fR upon reaching the end of file (\fBEOF\fR).

.SH DIAGNOSTICS
When a command is not found, \fBhsh\fR prints an error message to \fBstderr\fR in the following format:
.PP
\fBshell_name: line_number: command: not found\fR

.SH MEMORY MANAGEMENT
The shell strictly manages dynamic memory:
.IP "\(bu"
The \fBgetline\fR buffer is freed in the main loop.
.IP "\(bu"
The argument array is freed after every execution.
.IP "\(bu"
Copies of the \fBPATH\fR variable (via \fBstrdup\fR) are freed after command resolution.

